Inflation surges in Europe due to food prices
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant increase in food prices.
November's price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, after 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation was recorded at 3.1 percent, the Luxembourg statistics office of the Union reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issue banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the base interest rate, with the reduction, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, leading to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must “destroy” inflation so that it doesn’t have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation is a record of 3.3 percent for 15 years; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to soaring food and energy prices.
The futures price of wheat rose by 88 percent, and the soy price reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets rose by 52 percent this year, and last month it already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain about 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
