The most expensive is Auchan, almost a fifth of the price of Tesco
Hypermarkets in the Budapest business triangle maintained last year's, on average, 16 percent increase in price levels, with the difference that this year there was no increase in VAT.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
The usual Christmas basket of Napi Gazdaság newspaper in the Budapest business triangle has grown by an average of 16 percent this year, but in all hypermarkets the price has shown an increase of well over a thousand forints.
Since the prices in supermarkets "flew" last December, the percentage due to the earlier high base did not show such a drastic increase.
However, it is certainly disheartening for consumers that what they could have bought last year at a price below nine thousand forints, they will not now buy for even ten thousand.
The daily economy consumption basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
The highest price of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, the consumer basket cost 6,800 forints.)
The price of Unica and live fish remained almost at last year’s level, but it was very expensive for cruel breasts, nuts and poppy seeds.
The prices of bread and flour corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we found a kilo of bread even for 139 forints.
The competition did not go with the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of a two-liter Coca Cola in a returnable bottle was below 200 forints, so even with a down payment, the product cost only 257 forints.
Even so, this year, according to the Napi Gazdaság newspaper’s consumer basket, Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, the prices in the Napi Gazdaság consumer basket increased Cora by 15 per cent compared to last Christmas, while Tesco and Auchan increased by around 18 per cent.
When comparing last year’s highest and this year’s lowest consumption basket, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year’s lowest and this year’s highest is 21 percent.
In forints, the increase was an average of 1,480.
The average price increase last year was 1,206 forints, with prices affected by VAT growth last Christmas.
It was this process that disrupted trade, and apparently the department stores were unable to decide how large the price range should be for individual products, as they could not predict what effect the change in prices would have on consumption.
(If a trader plans the speed of circulation of a given product incorrectly, he may lose a significant profit due to the price range adjusted to the intensity of circulation.)
Due to VAT, last year’s rise in the price of the Napi Gazdaság consumer basket was so extreme that the price of the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than in 2006, while the cheapest one had a price difference of 844 forints.
This year, the most expensive basket cost 1,630 forints more than last year and also the cheapest one cost 1,284 forints.
Compared to the previous two Christmas seasons, prices have risen disastrously, raising the price of daily consumer goods in hypermarkets by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, among other things, does not absolutely confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office: it measured a price increase in excess of 30 percent in 12 months for several staple foods.
In addition to flour, for example, in the case of eggs.)
In the latter case, however, according to the daily economy consumption basket, it seems almost impossible, because the price level of the product, quite expensive last year, showed a price increase of barely above 10 percent, given the base even in the worst case.
The flour suppliers appear to be in stronger positions than the egg suppliers, and they have also managed to push through a drastic price increase in international chains.
Hypermarkets in the business golden triangle do not complain, they still report a good year.
In our experience, most customers in the three stores they visit are no longer interested in prices.
Everything is bought by quanta, durable food is taken by wages.
On Wednesday morning, all three supermarkets were forming long queues at checkout as the number of visitors soared.
However, as we know, the turnover in the countryside is lower, many international chains complain that sales lag behind their plans, not only in the case of food, but also durable consumer goods.
In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overloading of disease control staff do not help, says the head of the National Epidemiological Centre.
In many places, they are also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site earlier this year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with MRSA infection, and due to the bacteria found in his body, one important operation could not be carried out yet.
By December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections due to multi-drug-resistant agents had been reported to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina B -czová, the head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant disease agents have been registered with certainty in hospitals, others are unknown.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin resistant gold staphylococcus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infection, morning infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given in an exaggerated or inappropriate way, the antibiotic-responsive bacterium develops into a highly antibiotic-resistant bacterium that spreads rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, for example, morning infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the head doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections belong to the daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of a disease agent is not investigated."
Resists antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treat them with rubber gloves and a mask, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions in domestic hospitals are not favourable for the prevention and spread of multidrug-resistant disease agents, says Karolina Boerczová.
Since this infection is typically found in hospitals and homes for the elderly, hospitals receiving patients should screen and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It is also important that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these tests.
Most cases are revealed when the patient suffers from a perceptible MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict guidelines for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical histories.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases.
Microbiological samples are even rarer for basic or outpatient treatment of patients, said Karolina B -r -czová.
Saved on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are serious deficiencies in hospitals as well.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in home hospitals.
On the contrary, rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we can also meet with the fact that in hospitals, which are in an unfavorable material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few caregivers and many patients, which increases the chances of infections.
According to Karolina, where the necessary protective measures are followed, such infections are demonstrably less or the further spread of the disease can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treating MRSA is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA and reduce its incidence.
The program seems to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a decreasing tendency.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) places the prevention of multi-resistance disease agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these agents among its priorities.
The police captain who caused the fatal accident was not drunk.
