Another 400 million euros for infrastructure
The agreement on three loan frameworks worth a total of EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed on Friday in Budapest by Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB).
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework of EUR 300 million for Hungary’s budget financing of transport and environment projects supported by the Cohesion Fund, with the parties having previously concluded a loan agreement of EUR 100 million, the contract now signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A loan agreement worth EUR 150 million is also used for budget financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for these purposes, with the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties have signed a contract for EUR 50 million, which the budget will use mainly for the research and development project of the University of Debrecen.
There was also talk about the 4th metro line.
The parties agreed that after Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the financing of the metro, it will return to whether and how the original treaty needs to be modified.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary with a total of EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on loans granted by the EIB with a waiting period of eight years and without a commitment commission shall be linked to the EURIBOR rate.
Bulgaria is an EU real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is overwhelming - the attention of the whole of Europe is turning to the previously somewhat neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who is buying on the EU’s still cheapest but fast-growing market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most sought-after Eastern European destination for real estate is now undoubtedly Bulgaria with its cheap ski apartments and houses on the sea coast.
Of the mountains, the most in the course of the area of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša, on the sea coast then Albena, Golden Sands, Sunny Beach, ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for properties around Kavarna and Balčik.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will attract investors sooner or later, and more and more people are buying in the vicinity of the cheap city of Ruse.
Also, the capital of Sofia is a promise of attractive options, business and office premises promise the highest return.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf resorts in Europe, becoming a popular destination in the next two seasons, in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Foresight investors are already buying in bulk, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are trying to change their lives and lifestyles at the same time.
Most customers come from England, but buyers also come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more often from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present here, along the Black Sea and in the ski paradises there are traditionally many Russian customers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgy Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settling people buy either renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros or dilapidated old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good accessibility and communication options, the proximity of a large city, shops and, as a rule, a local doctor is important for them.
The second category is the cottage buyers (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of increasing their value in the medium or long term.
The price of real estate in the capital is continuous, as the demand is getting stronger.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, but they have risen by 21 percent annually over the past five years.
The rise in property prices far exceeds the rise in wages.
Fodor and Hungarian 6%
According to the Minister of Environment and Water Management Gábor Fodor, the meetings of experts will be closed on Tuesday and the international conference on the climate regime after 2012 will continue with the ministerial meetings.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which addresses efforts following the period of emission reductions defined by the Kyoto Protocol in force until 2012.
At the moment, there is a heated debate between developing and developed countries about them.
The United States has also announced that it does not wish to negotiate precise figures now, although it is in favour of an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 relative to 1990 levels.
The next big issue at the conference is whether developed countries, in addition to reducing emissions, will also agree to provide both material and technological assistance to countries that rely on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The grant fund, set by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member Governing Board, most likely within the framework of the UN’s World Environment Programme (GEF), according to the journal Piac és Profit.
The Hungarian 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection efforts and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said that the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the post-2012 agreement, and is ready to commit to a 30 per cent reduction if other developed areas of the world and developed countries are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments appropriate to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set themselves the target of a reduction of 5.2 percent, with the then 15 EU member states committing to 8 percent.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87, which our country will meet.
There is a lot going on in Bali, as an international agreement on long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would be postponed to 2012 with certainty, in which case the reduction commitments set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed up by a new emission reduction system, the necessity of which has also been highlighted by the UN’s Nobel Peace Prize-winning international scientific body in its latest report.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and an inevitable increase in the average temperature on Earth of more than 2 degrees Celsius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
British military forces are posting videos of their self-promoting actions in Iraq and Afghanistan on a video-sharing server.
The British Air Force (RAF) first took a liking to YouTube: special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of actions against the Taliban here since March 2006, the BBC reported.
The recordings, taken with a miniature camera attached to the helmet, are controlled by the Air Force Headquarters directing combat operations in the Kandahar area and then sent further to London, where they are transmitted to the Internet.
A political message is inevitable.
In this way, 139 recordings of British Air Force soldiers have already been accessed on the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have already looked at their "channel".
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenseheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and publishes footage of events in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force released the videos according to its original intent for recruitment purposes, and according to the Department of Defense, they are also good for acquainting the general public with the real purpose of the army's presence abroad.
"The promotion published in this form costs almost nothing compared to traditional TV recruitment ads," defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, "but it also necessarily carries a certain political message, as it confirms in a special form the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government."
The Americans played a game.
The military is worried that, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also sent to the server, capturing, for example, the death of soldiers: in somewhat hypocritical, "official" promotional films, officers at most talk about losses, but they do not perform a bloody form of combat.
After all, many videos from the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been released, but the British army has only just discovered them.
Americans recruit a little differently - using a shooting game called America's Army, which is free to download and in which the player can through a more or less faithful simulation get directly into the skin of soldiers.
