A giant strike is coming.
The League, or MOSZ, will set up its strike committee on Friday to coordinate Monday’s indefinite strike.
On Saturday, there will be a protest public assembly, on Monday - the day of the final vote on the law on health insurance - work will be stopped.
The action will certainly cause serious traffic disruptions, as rail traffic will almost completely stop and employees of the Budapest Transport Company (BKV) will also be on strike by 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League association together with the National Union of Workers’ Councils will introduce the details of the jointly organized Monday strike.
There will also be a strike commission LIGA - MOSZ, which will coordinate Monday's action.
A protest public assembly is held on Saturday, with unions joining the strike stopping work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
That is, there was no date set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act.
If Parliament does not pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the legislation is voted on, the strike commissions will meet and decide on the next steps.
According to Monday's agenda of the Parliament meeting, it is also possible that the Health Insurance Act will not be voted on until late in the evening or at night.
Due to the strike that begins on Monday, serious traffic disruptions can be expected: work on the railway will be stopped indefinitely, part of Budapest’s public transport may stop in the morning, and more than half of the companies will be Volán.
At the same time, half of the track will be closed in many parts of the country.
Numerous trade unions and civil society organisations have joined the strike call, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations announced a strike for an indefinite period, others announced a temporary cessation of work.
By Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (MÁV) and the Independent Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) were unable to agree on sufficient services, while more and more people travel by rail at the beginning of the Christmas holidays.
According to the previous announcements, from the beginning of operation until 1 p.m., the strike will take place at BKV, from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m. at Budapest Airport, a four-hour strike will be organized by the Trade Unions of Workers in the Energy Industry LIGA, and the Trade Union of Educators and the Democratic Union of Educators called for a 2- and 2-8-hour work stoppage respectively.
The Association of Hungarian Doctors will strike alternately throughout the country, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), belonging to the Cooperation Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), organizes a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands formulated by the League is for the government to revoke the health insurance reform proposal and submit a new concept for public discussion.
The second requirement is that the new method of calculating pensions, effective from next year, be introduced gradually.
Third, to ensure the possibility of inclusion in the scheme before 2010 for early retirement for the relevant branches of work.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), belonging to the League trade union, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport regarding railway branches, and expects a different offer.
Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the country's risk
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the entire region in several ways, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Institute of Political Capital.
In the context of the Hungarian Guard’s activities, the greatest political risk is posed by the fact that “the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary may soon lead to violent ethnic clashes”.
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is probably aimed at provoking such an action, the research institute adds.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of the Hungarian political representatives: "public discussion of the Romani question was left by the representatives of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy based on the Romani-Hungarian contradiction."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the Hungarian Guard's activities, according to the research institute, "largely damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of faith in the country's stability and its democratic maturity".
As part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has been receiving increasing publicity and vehemence since the autumn of 2006, several organizations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, calling themselves "national militia" associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civic associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the case of natural disasters, invasion of the homeland, disruption of order), in addition to pointing out the inability of the police, the army, or the state," he adds.
He goes on to note: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap all sorts of political efforts built on society’s resistance to politics and parties in civilian attire.
Thus, the emphasis on civility and the form of the association in the case of these groups serves not only to avoid the legal obstacles of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been pointed out in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, while the ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries, citing the establishment of the Hungarian Guard, want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this can have an impact on the political stability of the region,” he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
For example, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
Against the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard, there are mass Romani riots that broke out in one of the Sofia districts (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU used this to establish a guard, saying the organization's goal was "national militia".
She said there had been "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria over the past 17 years, but the country remained inactive and indifferent, according to the Political Capital Institute.
He added that the initiative sparked a heated debate among the Bulgarian public.
