Holidays are not free everywhere
In Hungary, the days off are set by law and it has become common practice to move working days around the holidays, which is expected less often next year.
In the European Union and in America, the holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and national holidays and public holidays.
Days of rest are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year here: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a working holiday - on the New Year's Eve just so that people can relax after New Year's Eve.
There are a total of 11 free holidays throughout the year.
The national holiday is March 15, celebrating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, a commemorative day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the foundation of the state, on May 1, work, on November 1 and 2, we remember the deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, the two-day holidays are Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our public, national or religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend, it has become the practice to move the working day in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of long weekends is that we stay in the workplace and at school the previous Saturdays.
The day immediately preceding or following the holiday has been regulated by a special decree of the Minister of Labour for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and their employees, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or, with regard to their purpose, also operate on business days.
This year there will be a change in the working order only around the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because, according to experience, most people will "work" in advance between Christmas and New Year's Eve or use the holidays saved in this way.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle, respectively at the end of the week, so the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar is transformed around the holiday of work, so that then the workers can stay at home for four days of taste.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, will be a day of rest.
The next move is related to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, the work will take place instead of Friday, October 24.
However, the end of the year next year will be able to take place completely in the sign of holidays, because from December 24 almost everywhere will have nonstop holidays, despite the fact that New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
Six little things you can do to annoy your colleagues
The emails we forget to send, the voicemails we never get, the innocent lies we hardly notice anymore: all of this makes everyday life in the workplace “more varied.”
The question is whether you will get used to these minor inconveniences, or put on gloves and unclear situations that can make others angry, you will deliberately avoid.
Tips.
"I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you they were looking for you from the marketing department," a colleague tells you.
That you missed a meeting because of it?
At best, he regrets it and tries to correct it, or calls the marketing department and says that he forgot to deliver the message (this is a less common solution).
Most often, the matter is solved with one apology.
Before making an embarrassing apology, it is good to think about what you can do to prepare unpleasant moments for your colleagues, and consciously try to prevent it.
Are you borrowing something that isn’t yours?
There’s nothing more unpleasant than reaching out for a document, an office item, or your phone, and they’re not there.
Do you remember putting a stapler on your desk yesterday, but it's gone by morning?
Or did you discover a pen on a colleague’s desk that you thought was lost?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without permission, otherwise they will be rightfully angry at you for going through their things.
Do not take envelopes or adhesive papers out of the office, as they can be uncomfortable if you run out of them early and you will need them immediately.
Rumors about the private lives of colleagues?
There is no good way to stop the spread of rumors.
Who, who, what was he doing?
Where and why?
Don’t put your personal information on everyone’s face!
When one of them shares his innermost secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Lock in what you have heard, and in his absence, do not discuss it with your colleagues, even when others know about his things.
Do you report your absence for no reason?
If you call the office and report your absence, citing a severe headache, because you are not feeling well, or you think that today you would rather rest, remember that someone else will have to do your work, urgent tasks and work for which they have a certain deadline for you.
Take care of your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you will not go to work the next day, or that something may happen that will make you need to stay home, report it so that your colleagues and managers will not be confronted with your absence until the next day.
Humiliation, giggles, phone calls
Have you fallen into a job that will grossly pull you out of the giggles of your colleagues?
Have you inadvertently witnessed a phone conversation that would be better not to hear at all?
Don’t disturb your co-workers by grunting, chanting, loud talk (over their heads), or stomping, constant cursing, loud discontent.
All this can be disruptive even when they are not involved in a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for their mistakes?
If something is not timely or you have forgotten to send an important letter or message, do not blame others for your forgetfulness!
Do not refer to the possible chaos reigning in the office and noisy colleagues!
Admit it if you made a mistake and someone paid for it, and repair the damage!
Ask how you could make things right, correct negligence!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Sweatpants and slippers: comfortable clothes for home, but not suitable for the office!
Do not wear clothes for leisure, even if your profession allows it!
Do not be careless, honor your colleagues and yourself by coming to the office in a regular dress - and if your profession requires it, nice and elegant!
