In the summer, he managed to earn half a billion euros from the American crisis.
He saw the opportunity at the beginning of the year.
In February, reports began to appear that so-called sub-prime mortgages, provided to low-income clients or those who had problems with repayment in the past, would have problems.
This crisis had no impact on the economy as a whole.
Kerviel didn't believe it and bet right.
At the end of the year, its profit reached 1.6 billion euros.
"When I made my first half billion, I didn't know how to announce it," Kerviel admits, adding that he definitely didn't keep anything for himself.
He admits throughout the interrogation that he falsified the records in such a way that they could not be found out.
He even managed to fool the bosses, even though the Eurex exchange became interested in his business.
Risk was Profit
Was he afraid to find out?
I don't think so.
"I thought the simple fact that I made $1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them."
Where did he get the will to risk so much?
He had to work out his position gradually.
He joined the Société Générale in 2000, just after graduating from the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was around $51,000.
Two years later, he was already an assistant broker and in 2005 became a standalone broker with an annual salary of $90,000.
He knew that he would never earn as much as anyone else.
“I knew from my first interview in 2005 that they were looking at me.
Because of my education and also because of my professional and personal development," Kerviel told investigators.
But shortly after his arrival, the first big success came.
Thanks to the shares, Allianz made a profit of half a billion euros in the bombing of London.
And that was the trigger mechanism - he wanted more.
As long as you're making money, we'll let you
"It's like a snowball," he told police.
But the bosses knew about it, or rather, they knew.
"As long as I was making money, they were turning a blind eye."
But then came the morning earlier this year.
He lost a billion euros in one day.
After the weekend in mid-January, he wanted to wipe it out.
When he arrived at work on Monday, he was no longer working at the bank.
A few days later, the bank reported that it had lost five billion euros.
And how did they find him?
He became a suspect because of his vacation.
“I’ve only had four days in the last year.
