Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to jointly fight the crisis in the financial markets.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be auctioned into the currency markets.
In these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will send $40 billion to the auction, while the other 24 will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step is intended to address the economy’s greatest difficulties, i.e. the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,” Bernard Baumohl, of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group, wrote in his report to clients.
“Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl said.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to non-performing loans, primarily in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
"Central banks must be really worried about what might happen next when they decide to do this," said Amro Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are worried that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will be expensive to lend to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with possible impacts on global economic growth.
Central banks have decided to do so after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still worried about borrowing money from each other, despite the fact that central banks of the US, Canada and Britain lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
Some analysts do not believe that the move by central banks will help to stave off the crisis, because it does not solve the underlying problem, and that is the collapse of the US real estate market.
