The national debt will rise to $1 trillion in 2009.
For every Czech, the national debt amounts to over CZK 84,000.
Total debt rose to CZK 842.7 billion at the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow CZK 159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the Ministry reduced the plan to CZK 152.8 billion due to better development of the state budget management.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose to CZK 842.7 billion at the end of September.
In the nine months of this year, it increased by CZK 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, it has decreased by CZK 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance today confirmed its data on the state debt from early October.
For every Czech, there is a debt of over 84,000 crowns.
Over the last year, the state has been indebted by more than CZK 111 billion.
"For now, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for next year, we could exceed the billion crowns threshold only in 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and a trillion crowns," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told news server iHNed.cz.
Vladimír Pikora, an analyst at Next Finance, says: “We could reach over one trillion in 2009.
When exactly will depend on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it turns out that the situation on the political scene would change, politicians would be willing to save more, it could move to 2010.
But I don’t anticipate this change,” he said.
Debts are rising
The state debt is a central government debt and is primarily created by the accumulation of government budget deficits.
Government debt is financed by treasury bills, government bonds, direct loans or, for example, loans from the European Investment Bank.
So far this year, the state’s internal debt has risen by 38.5 billion to CZK 719.4 billion.
So far this year, the state’s foreign debt has increased by CZK 1.7 billion to CZK 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable national debt reached CZK 803.3 billion at the end of September and has fallen by CZK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the national debt has increased to 6.5 years.
Total debt increased by 13 percent year-on-year in the first to third quarters, which is really a lot for how the economy is doing.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated for bonds, where the increase is 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand, it shows that there will be something to trade with when there is pension reform," Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The strategy of financing and managing the state debt for 2007 shows that the government planned to borrow CZK 159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the Ministry reduced the plan to CZK 152.8 billion due to better development of the state budget management.
The amount is mainly a deficit of the state budget, which will probably reach CZK 76 billion this year instead of the expected CZK 91.3 billion.
It also includes the planned maximum resources for the Czech Consolidation Agency of CZK 13.3 billion, a ten-billion reserve for the payment of pensions, the financing of government bonds worth CZK 43 billion and repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank in the amount of CZK 1.8 billion.
A woman is due to appear in court in Khartoum today for giving the name to a teddy bear.
The British teacher, who was tried in Sudan for insulting Islam, was sentenced to 15 days in prison by a Khartoum tribunal on Thursday evening and was expelled, her lawyer said.
