Our story actually begins in the month of September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old pupils to choose a name for the class teddy bear.
"Eight names will be heard from the mouths of the children, among them Hasan, Abdullah and Mohamed," says school principal Robert Boulos.
After voting in class, 20 of the 23 children will eventually choose Muhammad as their favorite name.
Of course, Muhammad is the name of a Muslim prophet, but above all, it is a very common first name in Sudan.
The children then created a book for their class with a picture of a teddy bear accompanied by a caption: "My name is Muhammad".
The bear itself had no label with this name on it, but the problem is in the very depiction of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
Gillian Gibbons, a fellow Muslim who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said she knew her well and would never do anything that could be offensive to any religious belief: “I only regret asking children to vote for a name,” he said.
