In the end, failure.
Serbs and Kosovo Albanians ended the sixth and final round of talks in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome differing views on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that both sides were unable to reach a status agreement," European negotiator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
His American counterpart, Frank Wisner, stressed that peace in the area was "at stake" and appealed to Belgrade and Pristina to heed their commitments to keep the peace and be ready for dialogue even after the negotiations ended.
"We do not expect violence in the near future, but we are entering a difficult period," he added, adding that "it is clear that the situation is tense."
Negotiations end on December 10
Troika negotiators, composed of representatives of the European Union, the United States and Russia, will travel to Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the province, where 90 percent are Albanian-speaking, could be seen in a clearer light on December 10, when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian negotiator Alexander Bocan-Kharchenko are due to report to the UN Security Council.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, mark the sixth and final round of negotiations since the UN mandated the Troika in August this year.
Americans and Europeans expect the talks to close on December 10.
On the other hand, the Russians, who previously blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the UN Security Council, insist that the negotiations continue beyond this deadline.
"Russia has been and remains in favour of a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Bocan-Kharchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of administration by the international community, the West sees Kosovo's independence under EU supervision as the only viable solution.
Pristina declares that if the Security Council does not decide in its favour, it is prepared to declare independence unilaterally.
Belgrade insists on extended autonomy.
"Unfortunately, we have not reached any agreement," said Fatmir Sejdiu, the president of the Kosovo government, in a hotel in Baden, where these "last chance negotiations" have been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former rebel commander of Kosovo Albanians and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
However, he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to the past, which led to murders and deportations".
"Domino effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadić, on the other hand, believes that the compromise is still under consideration and has warned the Albanian majority in Kosovo about the consequences of a possible unilaterally declared independence of the province.
Belgrade is said to be particularly concerned about the "domino effect" in an area that is still unstable due to the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"But for Serbia it does not mean," he said, "that compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that all decisions be taken solely by the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has veto power.
"Kosovo parliament to have final say"
"For Serbia, only a solution from the Security Council is acceptable," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Koštunica said.
“This meeting lasted two years.
It must end as it began: on the soil of the Security Council."
Fatmir Sedjiu told reporters that "the last word on status will be given to the Kosovar parliament," adding that if there was a unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population, it would be "by agreement" with the West.
