Loaded memory
After more than sixty years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which recount the fate of the 17.5 million victims of Hitler’s regime, are opening up to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored in Bad Arolsen (Hess) were only accessible for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
Eleven states in charge of archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians' free access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to examine "especially the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the alleged homosexuality or mental disabilities of some of the victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants set up by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor subjected to civilian citizens, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at Berlin's Technische Universität, in 2006.
