Congress approves MiFID transposition effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary deliberations that ended today with a vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected to a public hearing the ordinances that are developing the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of individual parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the effective functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between individual supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable the provision of financial advisory services to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons, and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments is increased by adding to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems that will compete with current stock brokers.
Furthermore, the Act obliges firms providing investment services to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of coping with risk on the market and requires to keep a report of all operations carried out to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
During a hearing with the Congressional Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which stands out that securitised receivables were considered a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor that was demonstrated by what occurred in the U.S. with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
Moreover, the directive's transposition has been used to legally define the functions that bachelors in economics and business management can hold 30 years after the Royal Decree was passed in 1977, which sets out the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
