The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into the future of Earth
Yesterday, scientists announced that Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live.
Data from the orbiting European station show that the planet is even more similar to Earth’s headstrong twin than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago there were conditions on Venus similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and lower rotational speed have sent Venus on a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is ravaged by storms and hurricane-force winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which studied the planet for one year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the University of Oxford's Department of Physics and one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said: "It's becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different than on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to build a scenario in which Venus began, like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
