None of the two stand a chance of being nominated, but both remain in the game perhaps because they began to sound the alarm over immigration earlier and more strongly than the others.
At least on immigration, the candidates have roughly the same view: more austerity at the border, no tolerance for illegal migrants.
This topic, along with concerns about poisonous toys from China and other concerns with the outside world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the rift between libertarians and Christian conservatives.
But the debate became very uncomfortable when it came to other topics.
Mr. Giuliani was asked why he had supported the possession of firearms in the past.
John McCain and Mr Romney discussed whether the simulated heating technique should be considered torture.
One interviewer asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
Even though the Bible is his favorite book, Giuliani may not believe the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another questioner asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - who is now against all odds in a recent survey in Iowa due to his long-standing Christian conservatism - said the death penalty is unpleasant but necessary.
Under pressure to decide whether Jesus would agree, he said that Jesus was too smart to run, earning him a laugh.
The fight remains unusually open.
Mr Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with recent successes in raising money and Ron Paul's loud cheer at Wednesday's debate.
The two rebounded from the bottom, as the two wings of the party still could not agree on more familiar and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one of the candidates united the party very early and convincingly with the winning report of American greatness on the lips, winking at both wings of the party.
This time the party is divided and the result is far from clear.
The Labour Pains
Gordon Brown has once again found a trap to fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although it is customary in British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
No orders seem to have been sold, no bills at the Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked.
But the barricaded Gordon Brown would do without it being discovered that some wealthy businessman had for four years disguised the ruling Labour Party's contributions of 650,000 pounds (1.3 million dollars) under other people's names, and that the party had not reported it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and insulted the British intelligentsia by claiming that the decision was not influenced by polls, there was hope that he would secure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly witty deputy chairman of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of the troubled bank Northern Rock showed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative mischief.
A trio of retired generals launched a rebellion in the House of Lords; they protested cuts in military spending as they argued that being a commander of the armed forces was a part-time job.
Now there are multifaceted gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and their former internal discipline watchdog), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is irresistibly heading towards his end.
Despite this, governments can reach the tipping point behind which they find governance difficult.
The people don't trust politicians and they don't like them, but they usually put their mistrust aside when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not even be in office for long, this push is gone: state administration is becoming leaky, ministers are starting to brief, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one respect, Mr Brown's position is particularly complex, as he cannot take the position of a new broomstick compared to other political leaders.
However much he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the Northern Rock issues and the Treasury records are linked to the decisions that Mr. Brown made as Treasury Secretary.
And even though he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s troubles, such as a lengthy investigation into political party funding caused by “values for money,” voters can safely conclude that he was.
Yet Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
Those mistakes aren't as bad as the conservatives make them.
As for Mr. Bean, no one died or was outright deceived.
And the cure, however painful it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm, and lightly brutal government.
The recent commotion over political gifts is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charity, says he wished no publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not his.
The laws against the anonymity of large political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who could buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew of Mr. Abrahams's procedure but did not know it was illegal, will certainly be questioned thoroughly; so will Jon Mendlesohn, the chief Labour money-gatherer, who learned of the tricky donations in October.
But so far, Mr. Brown is not involved in any way; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these schemes, though the bulk of the payments did not take place until after his arrival in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He very quickly condemned this violation of the law by his own party, but diluted his resolve by resorting to a proven instrument, a commission to investigate the matter - led in addition by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown must do, such as find a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and move forward with a real reform of political party funding.
This would require Labour, who are in a tight spot, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the trade unions - the bitter pill for a dedicated party member like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
Conservatives now have a decent lead in polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way to carve out victory is with unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card Sharks
Does the subprime mortgage crisis affect the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to flutter excitedly around.
As the U.S. real estate market dwindles, predators have turned their attention to the credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if subprime mortgages become infected.
Signs of tension are obvious.
There is an increasing number of cases of default (with more than 30 days of delay in payment) and written off accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
Last month, HSBC said it had lost $1.4 billion in U.S. consumer credit, also due to insolvent credit card loans.
However, it is still too early to panic.
Depreciation and inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody’s, the third quarter’s insolvencies rate was almost a full percentage point below average.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
A change in U.S. personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which make up a large part of credit card losses; thus, the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would rise regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers had deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts monthly.
And confidence in the securities of secured credit cards is firm, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup predicts that emissions will be 25% higher in 2007 than last year.
There are certainly direct routes for spreading the infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when property equity loans dry up, consumers are more likely to go into debt over credit cards.
However, credit card issuers look at the cash flow rather than the value of collateral items, so falling home prices don’t necessarily mean a change in lenders’ credibility.
They can even be beneficial for lenders.
The incentive for consumers to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up the list of priorities to be repaid.
Card issuers are also able to respond more quickly and flexibly to stormier conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risk of a rapid change in the prices of guaranty items.
“It’s not like we’re just going to reassess all our loans one fine morning,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Even if the risk of explosion in the style of subprime mortgages is low, the danger of gradual weakening is much more real.
If lower house prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
UK bankers plead guilty in Enron case
The three British bankers, who were to be tried for their roles in a fraud linked to former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow, changed their statement on Wednesday and pleaded guilty.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby, and Gary Mulgrew were initially guilty of seven counts of fraud in which they, along with Fastow, were involved in financial fraud in 2000 -- enriching themselves at the expense of their employers -- they denied.
They were due to appear in court in January.
However, during the trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to one fraud.
The case of these three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, has been on the front pages for two years, which has taken the publishing proceedings.
In the United States, their case is one of the unsolved parts of an investigation launched after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges brought against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron crash.
The indictment against bankers -- who have earned the nickname "NatWest Troika" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to frame the fraud along with Fastow and his former chief aide Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in an Enron affiliate controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of many of the Enron scams that pushed Enron spiraling toward bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank rated its stake in this branch zero, but our three Britons knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
The company under Kopper's control bought the bank's stake in this branch for $1 million.
The incriminated bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in the Greenwich NatWest subsidiary.
But the $20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the indictment, the bankers received $7.3 million and Fastow, Kopper and others improved by about $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence at a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year and one-month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
All three Britons were free on a $1 million bond that ordered them to stay in the United States for the upcoming trial.
Enron, once the seventh largest company in the country, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks made it impossible to hide billions in debt or report failing speculation as profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value, and more than $2 billion in pension insurance.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's downfall.
Skilling is serving a 24-year sentence.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud, and other charges were expunged after he died of heart disease last year.
Moscow's powerlessness
The price of the Gulfstream G550, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and with enough fuel for a nonstop flight from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
For some of Russia’s rich, however, it’s a small amount to return.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers," says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of them are interested in so many places because it's for a tight family or a corporate president."
Mr. Firer sat in the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire Show, a four-day orgy of flamboyant consumption at the mammoth exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury suppliers built their stalls, hoping to lure the newly wealthy Russians into everything from mahogany-laden yachts to diamond-decorated car partitions that not even 50 Cent would be ashamed of.
Mr. Firer looked carefully at the bright orange Porsche in the next booth.
"It's a nice car, but against us it's dime and dime," he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private jets."
On the waves of oil, money is pouring into the Russian capital just as it did when Dallas had its days.
“We went through the same stage in the 1980s when some Americans became hugely wealthy and went to Europe, where they were viewed as materialists,” said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are becoming the world's most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, the luxury industry conference of Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, chairman of the LVMH Group, attracted to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like the Russian one.
(The conference is hosted by The International Herald Tribune, owned by The New York Times Company.)
According to Forbes, Russia has 53 billionaires with a combined net worth of $282 billion.
In addition, the Center for Economic and Financial Research published a report on the development of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, according to which there are 103,000 "second-rate" millionaires in Russia, whose wealth totals 670 billion dollars.
(The World Bank reports that in 2005, 15.8% of Russians lived below the subsistence minimum.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow -- and that's why we're all here," said Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative for London jewelry store David Morris.
She was at the fair for the first time, together with the Russian distributor of this brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"All women are finely groomed, and men are every man for a fortune."
When they walked through the halls in their evening dresses on Sunday evening, 21-year-old Evgenia Yumatova and five years older Svetlana Turovcova described themselves and their clients as millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I can't decide between Infiniti, Mercedes and Porsche," said Miss Yumatova, who was wrapped up in designer clothing like a red carpet veteran, next to whom Joan Rivers looks like a home hanger.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at fresh rich people, brand-controlled Russian buyers who are willing to sit out for a few hours in the road traffic so that they can walk around the warehouse, which gaudyly stirs Cadillac Escalade, platinum fish, M-venpick ice cream, tailor-made billiard tables, apartments in Dubai, plush Gund draughts and draughts.
Members of the general public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best," said Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the stall of the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft before reproducing Rembrandt's painting of a hand-painted blue tile in extra-life size.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in tinsel."
And indeed, local sellers say that Russians with old money (by Russian standards it is 10 to 15 years old) have already moved from flashy logos to little-known limited-edition brands that would never show up at a shopping fair.
Even so, several thousand people, whether millionaires, ambassadors of millionaires or simple tourists, flooded the fair halls every day.
Some of them were shopping.
The first day of the show, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the local general manager of King Koil beds, said he sold two silk, cashmere and cotton mattress sets, interwoven with gold threads, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager of A1 Moto, which equips high-end cars with high-end alarms, said his company sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that customises luxury cars, said he sold three chains for a $55,000 Rolls-Royce Phantom.
He showed a reporter a wheel of a car designed for a Russian casino owner that had a string coated with Swarovski crystals so that it looked like roulette.
Price: $22,000 for four of these.
"That Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a portrait of his wife from cubic zirconia, he doesn't have to ride those wheels yet," Mr. Karapetian said.
"He puts them in his garage with thirty to forty cars."
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said that the phrase "Russian millionaire" does not currently mean anything very exclusive, due to the large increase in the prices of local real estate.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already millionaires, at least on paper, if not in cash," he said.
"There are more of them than you think."
Those who are not millionaires could at least pretend to be wealthy at a stand operated by the Russian asset management firm Alliance Continental.
The company erected four red British-style telephone booths stuffed with a column of counterfeit notes worth a million dollars.
Azad Karryev, the company’s marketing manager, said his team had printed 500,000 fake bills for the Millionaires’ Fair.
The passers-by stopped to throw around piles of money, or let friends take pictures of them resting in the middle of a substitute fortune, or simply stuffed their pocket a few million.
"You know, in Moscow everyone can feel like a millionaire," Mr. Karryev said.
