The hope that the Fed will lower interest rates leads to the strengthening of world stock exchanges
Stock prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after market hopes that the Federal Bank would try to calm borrowing conditions by further cutting interest rates were bolstered by reassuring remarks by the vice-chairman of the US central bank.
The stock markets surged in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second behind Ben Bernanke, the Fed’s chairman, said that in responding to continued pressure in financial markets, executives must be “flexible and pragmatic.”
As part of an apparent effort to calm the irritable markets amid signs of a resurgent credit crunch, Mr Kohn said the recent outbursts had "partly reversed some of the improvements in the functioning of the markets in late September and October".
He also said that if the increased instability persists, the possibility that financial conditions for households and businesses will deteriorate further will increase.
Investors see these statements as a signal that the Fed is ready to deliver more fresh capital to the U.S. markets, and possibly further interest rate cuts, to stabilize credit conditions.
These remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid other bad news about the U.S. economy, as apartment sales in October showed record low numbers.
The consequences of the financial turmoil were underscored by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4% of its global workforce, as part of a cost-cutting effort to compensate for heavy losses caused by a failed bid to provide sub-prime housing loans in America.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to be abolished in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Index grew 331 points, or 2.55 percent, and closed at 13,289.40, while the more widely used S&P 500 index strengthened by 2.65 percent.
The London FTSE 100 rose by 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, and closed at 6,306.2, with the value of British blue-chips rising by more than 39 billion pounds.
Germany’s Dax index rose 2.6 percent and France’s CAC40 rose 2.3 percent.
Some time ago, credit tensions in the markets showed themselves to be in full force after these funds were lent to European commercial banks at a rate of 4.7% in the auction of the European Central Bank’s three-month money packages, the highest since April 2001.
The pressure on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and the ECB and release extra money into London’s money markets has increased, with the rates of the three-month British interbank loans “Libor” rising after uninterrupted growth since November 12 to their maximum since the end of September - 6.59 percent.
England must decide: Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
There are two dilemmas, one almost as difficult as the other.
Who will be number six on the bat for England this weekend in Kandy, Owais Shah, or Ravi Bopara?
And, in a broader context no less relevant than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who is to make this decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the select committee who holds the position at best in borrowed time, has Peter Moores, the head coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, making the decision to help, and because Hugh Morris, the head manager of the English team, is beginning to fill the table with applications for the position of national selector, albeit not necessarily full-time.
He who is not placed sixth on the bat will be unhappy, but life is often not fair and sport is not.
It is not easy to find what gets one to the top of his profession, while someone else never gets past the lower level, sometimes due to a lack of luck rather than ability.
It is not only in cricket that selection is difficult and requires judgement, which in the end must always be subjective.
Is it the right time for Bopara to move up?
It's fair to Shah, if it is?
We could ask the same question in another area, let's say here: John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both smart young executives with good education and insight in the field, should be promoted to the commission - there is only room for one.
Who's to say which level is right for a cricketer if he can't get a chance to drop or sail to the next one?
Of course, numbers have a big impact on decision-making, but so do opportunities.
In a team, the cricketer must catch the captain's eye at the right moment, whether to take a wicket, and the batsman needs regular chances at starting positions, if he is ever to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching a collector's eye is more complicated.
For example, last season there were many better ones that James Anderson, whose place in the first Test seems certain, even if Stephen Harmison declared himself healthy and pitched like an artilleryman.
Anderson took 32 wickets in the first class in 33 runs for each.
Chris Tremlett took just 29 at the same mediocre average, but both had their moments at the highest level and are hoping for more.
Whether he plays at Asgiriya Shah Stadium or Bopara can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice may start or finish the career of both, or it may not have much influence.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka Gareth Batty played in every Test and gave good performances in the first class, five wickets and 40 runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, who at the same time was fighting for his place, who eventually became a stable Test cricketer, who, in addition, despite having scored twice a hundred points in Australia against Australia, may still be underestimated.
Graveney, Vaughan and Moores are more likely to follow their conservative instincts after one more discussion following today's practice at Asirgiya Stadium, preferring Shah's greater experience over Bopar's youthful exuberance.
There are arguments for both.
For Shah, his sparkling and valuable debut Test innings speak at 88 points in Mumbai and 32 in first class versus six Boparov, who is, at twenty-two, seven years younger and has excellent statistics against spin pitches.
However, Shah made only ten runs in two innings in May against the Caribbean in Test at Lord's, his home ground in Middlesex, and this, along with an immediate rejection of the selectors when Vaughan wanted to re-cast him for another match, his batting seems to have taken away something of the vigor that was so evident in Mumbai.
In contrast, the Essex universal has joie de vivre in its bones.
Nothing scares him on the cricket field, and his off-field behavior symbolizes a recently overturned four-wheel-drive car at the exhibition day of the English team's car sponsor, Volkswagen.
He survived with minor injuries and probably shock, but the first thing he pulled out was his Vodafone (and of course also sponsored) and called Alastair Cook, his teammate who was watching from a distance, to ask him excitedly, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is definitely better in the field, his medium-speed skid pitches on local pitches, which seem to suit him, he gives out effectively and bats confidently and skillfully.
Choosing the right person is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Perhaps this is the true art of choice.
Personally, I am in favour of Bopara getting his chance now, which is not to say that Shah will not excel if, as the Ceylon tea leaves suggest, he will be the one to play here next weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to the fight against al-Qaeda
The first buses full of Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, dumping refugees who had run out of money or expired visas, and others hoping the city would return to normal life.
Some even returned to fight the gunmen who had driven them from their homes.
The Mansour bus station was already packed with refugees from Syria and Jordan before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy, returning by private transport.
"I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad," said Sabah al-Kubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
