Little Saarland, good education
The smallest federal state of Germany plays a leading role in vocational education, excelling even in the international focus of its universities.
Only in one area of education does the Saar worry about the same shortage as the rest of Germany.
"To the man who is not from Saarland, I explained yesterday for the fiftieth time that we are not French" - this self-ironic slogan appears on posters in Saarland on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the birth of this smallest federal state.
France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saar education system, which is ranked fifth in monitoring the education of the Cologne Institute for Economic Research (IW).
Traditionally, universities have worked closely with the surrounding countries.
The University of Saarbruecken was founded in 1948 by the French.
To this day, students can finish their studies with a double or even a triple diploma.
This corresponds to a relatively high proportion of foreign students, which is 15.6%.
After all, an above-average number of Saar children are admitted to university - many of them even without studying at the gymnasium.
“In Saarland, the professional education system is used,” says Axel Pl’nnecke, an IW education expert.
By giving more than one in five young people the right to study at a vocational school, the Saarland is more than 7% above the German average.
Compared to the rest of Germany, Saarland has a wealth of opportunities for combining practical and academic education.
The opportunities to study two fields of study are second best in all of Germany in terms of population.
Despite a practice-oriented education and increasing demand, the number of engineering graduates has fallen by a third in recent years.
That is why the Saar Ministry of Education has now ordered universities to create a promotion campaign for engineering disciplines.
