Anyone who combines the words Sweden and wooden crates does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Do you?
Wooden crates currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Most of his listed ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brillo boxes" of 1968, comes an internal research of the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm with the result that brought disillusionment; six "Brillo boxes", which in 1995 the Museum Moderna Museet donated to its former director Pontus Hultillo, are copies - like most of the other boxes on the international market "B.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden crates that were based on the red-and-white design of Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their originals, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, but they are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of the fifteen crates that rightfully entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now lies in the fact that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred crates were made and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 of Hultén's crates were made in Malmo for the exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol was already three years dead.
In addition to the six Brillo boxes that are owned by the museum, Lars Bystrom, the head conservator of the Moderna Museet, also examined three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and, after their plywood plates were painted with the base paint and sanded, were painted with oil white paint with a brush.
On the other hand, the structure of the 1990 copies showed that the paint was applied directly to the plywood plate without the previous primer - besides, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list," said Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board organization in New York City does not come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into these "core allegations" that have been made about soap powder boxes.
But the organization remains in unrelenting silence.
